social_posts.post_text: I needed more weaving loom shuttles for my students… so I tried 3D printing one and it worked! Haha 😍

Guess what?! @oakcreativedesigns will have a booth at Reviving the Islamic Spirit @risconvention on Dec 23rd-25th at the Metro Toronto Convention Centre. I will be there too for a few days to help them man the booth, and would love to see you there! Check out their full catalog of items on their website at www.oakcreativedesigns.com to get a peek at all their amazing hand crochet toys that will be available at the Grand Bazaar.

One of my favourite things to do is try out new art projects with the kids in my classes. I think this knitted wire art was a hit, the kids learned not only loom knitting but also got super creative with their wire designs!

I always find it amazing how we are all drawn towards different things. How we all have a unique spark and an interest that we become passionate about and can share with our community. What are you passionate about?

We attended a beautiful event for Islamic Heritage month (yes I know, a month late, but that’s okay!), it was hosted by the Muslim Homeschool community in my area and the general homeschool community was invited to attend. The children prepared presentation boards around the topic of “What does Islam mean to me?”, there was a wonderful potluck buffet, a few youth MCs, and some interactive hands on activities too!

My kids prepared the welcome poster along with an art activity. The Islamic geometric art activity was an idea from www.SamiraMian.uk under the free tutorials section on her website. Such a great activity for kids (and adults!) who want to get started with Islamic Geomtric Art.

A little hand sewing button goodness done by my after school Hand Sewing class!

When women support each other, incredible things happen.

There are only a few more days left until @risconvention and we can’t wait! There are a lot of last-minute details to still take care of but we are being supported by team of wonderful women.

One of these exceptional women is our dear friend Evangeline from @handmadebeginnings. Evangeline has been an integral part of Oak Creative Designs ever since we first started our vocational training program for refugee women in 2016. 

Her creative ideas, encouragement, and technical support really helped us build a foundation where we could effectively share the work of our talented artisans. Not only has she sold our products at various pop up shops around the GTA, but has she even started our website and this Instagram page for us! 

We have worked with Evangeline to also develop our sewing project. She has trained and hired our artisans to sew some of her timeless products such as her Ramadan Calendar, Arabic Alphabet Chart, Bibs and Dua Pillows.

Drop by our booth (#1131) to meet Evangeline from December 23-24. Make sure to also check out her page @handmadebeginnings to see the many amazing projects that she is working on.

Stay tuned for tomorrow's introduction to another member of our booth team. Any guesses on who it could be?

I started my business when Asiyah was 2 years old and she’ll be sweet 16 this spring! 😭 They grow so fast! I started off with a basic sewing machine, which was actually my dowry present (I know I’m such a nerd 🤓) and some gifted fabrics. My philosophy has always been slow and steady, and that I am not out to compete with anyone except a past version of myself. My kids and family have always been my number one priority with my biz coming second, and if that means it takes decades to grow, then that’s cool by me. 🙂

When I was a kid I wanted to be either Mr. Dressup or Mr. Rogers and maybe Mrs. Frizzle. When my students give me little cards, or a hug, or a thank you, I am always genuinely surprised, but then I think nice, I’ve made it into the cool teacher’s club 😎, now I can die happy, lol. If you can be anything, be kind. 🫰

P.S.- the beautiful artwork on the cards in this video, are by my long time friend @art.by.aruba, go check her out! Her mom taught me how to read Quran when I was a kid, she was one of the coolest teachers. 😍
Don’t let the little things set you back, don’t give up and keep going! ✨ #bintiedoll

My goal is to not only have students make cool things to take home, but to learn about all the tools and neat techniques they can use to unleash every creative idea their imaginations can come up with, for years and years to come! ✨ #handmadebeginnings

I often sew pants for my girls. In the girls section of most shops you can find either a) jeans or similar highly constructed stiff feeling pants or b) leggings, both of which my daughters refuse to wear. 

Their requirements are that their pants need to have an elasticized waist, be baggy, and also be a nice soft cotton. Check, check, check. (Also why is it sooo difficult to find pants for girls like this?)

I drafted the pattern for these pants using one of my daughter’s favourite (and super worn out!) pants as a template and added pockets of course. It was all refashioned from a preloved bedsheet and is perfect for breezy summer days playing outside at the park or hiking through the woods. Now I just need to make a few more. It sure does feel good to get back into some sewing after a long (and much needed) break!

I finally organized my unruly jumble of ribbons! 🎀 I am not the most organized person, so this will help me be more productive for sure when creativity strikes! 

Also I know how crazy it must seem to have drawers and drawers of ribbons and trims, but my most popular products - Ramadan calendars and Bintie dolls relied on them, so I’ve built up quite the collection over time 🙈. Well I have to say, I’m super excited to get back into making!

One day I will go in and wind all the threads onto bobbins.. maybe.. like when my kids are grown and I have time, or perhaps I’ll convince my kids it’s a fun fine motor activity and get them to do it for me now, haha.

DIY magnetic pin dish- on the Blog today! 📍 

One of the number one rules I tell my students is to always put their pins back in their pin cushion or magnetic dish tray when they are done with them. No one wants to be stepping on any pins! Pins are notorious for rolling around and falling on the ground and safety is always number one when sewing. 

You can make your very own one of kind magnetic pin dish, find out how on the blog!

14 years ago I organized a community craft bazaar with my friend @memonahossain to raise money for Gaza. 14 years later, a new generation, my children, are participating in craft bazaars to raise money for Gaza. 

A few takeaways from this are: 

1. Use your talents and strengths (and encourage your children to use their talents and strengths) to raise awareness, raise funds, and bring community together for this cause. For me my jam is art, but find your strength whether it be public speaking, writing, researching, protesting, social media, etc.

2. Don’t burn yourself out, we need to be in this for the long haul. Every atom’s weight of good you do will be one positive contribution, so don’t underestimate the amount of support you can give. It will vary from day to day, season to season. If you are unable to take the lead, support those who are. Keep doing what you can, don’t give up.

3. Keep educating. Educate yourself. Educate your children. Educate your friends and community. 🇵🇸

(Photos: first slide, my daughter’s art for sale. second slide, old craft bazaar poster I made 2009)

Assalamu Alaikum + Hello, just popping in here to share some news as we wrap up the year. Alhumdulillah (All praise be to God) I had a baby boy last month. It’s why I’ve been quiet on here lately and for much of 2023 actually. My kiddos and I are all super smitten with baby and we are settling in and adjusting to our new normal as a family of 7.

I had some questions about my shop, so I’ll update you on that. I will not be selling any handmade products, nor conducting any in person sewing classes for a while. But you can always learn with me through my online sewing course which I will be regularly updating and which will be my main focus in 2024.

Thank you all for your continued support of my small biz through it’s ups and downs and different evolutions as it changed to fit my life and family throughout the years. Being able to work from home and homeschool my children is a huge blessing that I don’t take for granted. Thank you for being part of it all! 

May Allah bring about an immediate ceasefire 🍉 and end the occupation. May Allah bring peace, healing and home to the Palestinians. May 2024 be the year that we see a #freepalestine Ameen.

“In every stitch you make, you breathe life into a tradition that is vital to the identity and resilience of the Palestinian people. Cross-stitching, particularly the art of Tatreez, is a form of resistance that transcends boundaries. It’s a symbol of unity and a testament to the enduring spirit of a culture that has withstood the test of time.” - @threadsofdiaspora 

Here is my completed square for the Threads of Diaspora community project organized by the Canadian Palestinian Cultural Association of Edmonton. @cpca.edmonton @threadsofdiaspora

#ThreadsofDiaspora #StitchtoResist #FreePalestine

As a sewing instructor and seamstress, I have a bit of an obsession with textile art. I always gravitate to the textile areas of museums, and to textile shows. Lately, I have really been enjoying learning about Palestinian embroidery, known as Tatreez. I took a class with Danah @motherofpearl91, where she showed us how to cross stitch a Cypress Tree. I plan to follow her suggestion and make an entire embroidery sampler with different Palestinian motifs insha’Allah. The book pictured above is my very favourite “Textiles of the Islamic World”, by John Gillow, with a beautiful section on Palestine. 

(Throwback post- this pic and caption was originally posted in July 2021. Stay tuned for my updated sampler! It has come a long way since I made this first piece).

#tatreez #palestiniantextiles #islamicart

My second square for the Threads of Diaspora community quilt project organized by the Canadian Palestinian Cultural Association of Edmonton. @cpca.edmonton @threadsofdiaspora 

It was such a joy to stitch these, I got a lot of practice in trying to keep the backs of my work clean and tidy too. There is something about the geometric patterns and the repetitive nature of this craft that is just so soothing. 

Check out @threadsofdiaspora to see their recent news feature about the project. Swipe to see the quilt coming along.

#threadsofdiaspora #stitchtoresist #freepalestine
